article.headline: Miller plays big off bench as Monarchs fall again
article.linkText: Sting hold reeling Monarchs to 29-percent shooting
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Kelly Miller scored 16 points and the
Charlotte Sting limited the Sacramento Monarchs to 29 percent
shooting in a 70-51 victory Friday night.

	   Miller was 7-for-8 from the field in just 16 minutes, while
Charlotte Smith added 14 points and Andrea Stinson had 11 for the
Sting (13-8). Charlotte won its fourth straight game and ended a
six-game losing streak to the Monarchs.

	   "I felt pretty on tonight,'' Miller said. "It helps a lot when
you have a hot hand and my teammates did a great job of getting me
the ball.''

	   Yolanda Griffith scored a season-high 16 points and grabbed 10
rebounds in her fourth game back from an injury to lead Sacramento
(4-16), which lost for the 11th time in 12 road games. Ruthie
Bolton added 11 points.

	   "You just can't win ballgames when you shoot like that,''
Monarchs coach Maura McHugh said. "I feel like we executed well
and got some good looks, but it was just one of those nights when
nothing would fall in the basket.''

	   Smith's 3-pointer capped a 10-2 run to start the second half and
gave the Sting a 45-26 lead. Sacramento got no closer than 10
points after that, as Charlotte led by as many as 22 points.

	   The Sting, who improved to 10-2 at home, have won their past two
games by a combined 46 points.

	   "I think we are really starting to gel,'' Charlotte coach Anne
Donovan said. "We're playing a lot of people and getting great
contributions from our bench. I'm very pleased.''

	   Kedra Holland-Corn hit a 3-pointer 24 seconds into the game to
give Sacramento the lead, but the Monarchs their next 15 shots over
a 10-minute span. Charlotte, the league's top 3-point shooting
club, was 4-for-5 from behind the arc during that stretch to take a
22-8 lead.

	   Charlotte led 35-24 at halftime despite Sacramento's 5-for-27
shooting. The Monarchs stayed in the game thanks to a 12-for-15
effort from the free throw line.

	   "We started off really flat and it was too late when we finally
started picking it up,'' Monarchs guard Ticha Penicheiro said.
"It's a disappointing loss after the big win we had in Miami the
other night.''

	   Sacramento beat the Sol 78-62 Wednesday, the Monarchs' only road
win of the season.
